text.tspan: Highlights (to be included on the body of the report):
- The effect of CLs removal switches between crowded and more dispersed
DSB clusters. The repair of two near DSBs (g = 4) is observed to be
slighly enhanced by keeping CLs in the DSB ends. On the contrary,
the repair of further DSBs (g =20) appears slighty enhanced by
removing those CLs. Those differences are observed specially for
- Removing CLs in DF makes the FET much slower and buffers the
encounter rate increment induced by the increasing connectivity.
- The size of the polymer at the instant of encounter (measured as
MSRG at encounter time) does not depend on the position of the broken
loci and seems to be also independant of the removal of CLs in DF,
depending on the initial number of CLs only.
- (To be discused also in other figure concerning anomalous diffusion)
The monomers average anomalous exponent (averaged over different folding scenarios,
ranging from Nc=2 to 58 with 600 realisations each and with DSBs fixed at A1 = 46 and
B1 = 54) decreases as we approach the center of the polymer and increases as we
approach around the DSBs. This difference becomes more evident when CLs in the
DF are removed. Besides, when CLs in DF are removed, while monomers around
DSBs reach superdiffusive regimes, surprsingly the DF ends themselves manifest
